# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1-phenylethanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] Phenylethanol is an aromatic alcohol, it has the role of mouse metabolite.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] It is a natural product and is found in *Cichorium endivia*, *Castanopsis cuspidata* and other organisms.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] 1-Phenylethanol is found in nature as a glycoside, together with its hydrolase β-primeverosidase in tea (*Camellia sinensis*) flowers.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] It is also reportedly present in cranberries, grapes, chives, Scottish spearmint oil, cheeses, cognac, rum, white wine, cocoa, black tea, filbert, cloudberries, beans, mushrooms, and endives.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] Racemic 1-phenylethanol is produced by the reduction of acetophenone by sodium borohydride.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] Alternatively, benzaldehyde can be reacted with methylmagnesium chloride or similar organometallic compounds to afford racemic 1-phenylethanol.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] Asymmetric hydrogenation of acetophenone by Noyori catalysts proceeds quantitatively (50 atm H2, room temperature, minutes) in >99% e.e.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] The organic oxidising agent ethylbenzene hydroperoxide yields 1-phenylethanol when reduced.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] Used for the epoxidation of propene, this coproduces propylene oxide, and is an important step in the PO/SM process for the production of styrene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] In the final step of the PO/SM process, dehydration of 1-phenylethanol yields styrene, analogous to many other dehydrations of alcohols to yield alkenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] While secondary to the direct dehydrogenation of ethylbenzene, the PO/SM method remains industrially significant.
[src:1-phenylethanol/1-phenylethanol] This route accounted for approximately 15% of styrene production in the United States in 1993, and has seen international development in the 21st century, especially in developing economies that have seen growth in demand for both styrene and propylene oxide.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] Phenethyl alcohol is prepared commercially via two routes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] Most common is the Friedel-Crafts reaction between benzene and ethylene oxide in the presence of aluminium trichloride.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] The reaction affords the aluminium alkoxide that is subsequently hydrolyzed to the desired product.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] The main side product is diphenylethane, which can be avoided by use of excess benzene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] Hydrogenation of styrene oxide also affords phenethyl alcohol.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] Phenethyl alcohol can also be produced by biotransformation from L-phenylalanine using immobilized yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] It is also possible to produce phenethyl alcohol by the reduction of phenylacetic acid using sodium borohydride and iodine in THF.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] Phenethyl alcohol is found in extract of rose, carnation, hyacinth, Aleppo pine, orange blossom, ylang-ylang, geranium, neroli, and champaca.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] It is also an autoantibiotic produced by the fungus *Candida albicans*.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] Fusel alcohols like phenethyl alcohol are grain fermentation byproducts, and therefore trace amounts of phenethyl alcohol are present in many alcoholic beverages.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] It is therefore a common ingredient in flavors and perfumery, particularly when the odor of rose is desired.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] It is used as an additive in cigarettes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] It is also used as a preservative in soaps due to its stability in basic conditions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] It is of interest due to its antimicrobial properties.
[src:1-phenylethanol/2-phenylethanol] The compound also enhanced disease-resistance enzyme activity without significantly affecting tomato fruit quality.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Acetophenone is formed as a byproduct of the cumene process, the industrial route for the synthesis of phenol and acetone.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] The cumene process is conducted on such a large scale that even the small amount of acetophenone by-product can be recovered in commercially useful quantities.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Acetophenone is also generated from ethylbenzene hydroperoxide.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Ethylbenzene hydroperoxide is primarily converted to 1-phenylethanol (α-methylbenzyl alcohol) in the process with a small amount of by-product acetophenone.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Acetophenone is recovered or hydrogenated to 1-phenylethanol which is then dehydrated to produce styrene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Commercially significant resins are produced from treatment of acetophenone with formaldehyde and a base.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] The resulting copolymers are conventionally described with the formula [(C6H5COCH)*x*(CH2)*x*]*n*, resulting from aldol condensation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] These substances are components of coatings and inks.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Modified acetophenone-formaldehyde resins are produced by the hydrogenation of the aforementioned ketone-containing resins.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] The resulting polyol can be further crosslinked with diisocyanates.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] The modified resins are found in coatings, inks and adhesives.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Acetophenone is an ingredient in fragrances that resemble almond, cherry, honeysuckle, jasmine, and strawberry.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] It is also listed as an approved excipient by the U.S.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] More common as a fragrance is the closely related 4-methylacetophenone.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Being prochiral, acetophenone is also a popular test substrate for asymmetric hydrogenation experiments.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Acetophenone is used for the synthesis of many pharmaceuticals.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Acetophenone occurs naturally in many foods including apple, cheese, apricot, banana, beef, and cauliflower.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, acetophenone was used in medicine.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] It was marketed as a hypnotic and anticonvulsant under brand name Hypnone.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] The typical dosage was 0.12 to 0.3 milliliters.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] It was considered to have superior sedative effects to both paraldehyde and chloral hydrate.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] In humans, acetophenone is metabolized to benzoic acid, carbonic acid, and acetone.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Hippuric acid occurs as an indirect metabolite and its quantity in urine may be used to confirm acetophenone exposure, although other substances, like toluene, also induce hippuric acid in urine.
[src:1-phenylethanol/acetophenone] Acetophenone is currently listed as a Group D carcinogen indicating that there is no evidence at present that it causes cancer in humans.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In organic chemistry, an **alkene**, or **olefin**, is a hydrocarbon containing one or more carbon–carbon double bonds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The double bond may be internal or at the terminal position.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Terminal alkenes are also known as **α-olefins**.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Acyclic alkenes, with only one double bond and no other functional groups (also known as **mono-enes**) form a homologous series of hydrocarbons with the general formula C*n*H2*n* with *n* being a >1 natural number (which is two hydrogens less than the corresponding alkane).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] When *n* is four or more, isomers are possible, distinguished by the position and conformation of the double bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes are generally colorless non-polar compounds, somewhat similar to alkanes but more reactive.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The first few members of the series are gases or liquids at room temperature.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The simplest alkene, ethylene (C2H4) (or "ethene" in the IUPAC nomenclature) is the organic compound produced on the largest scale industrially.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Aromatic compounds are often drawn as cyclic alkenes, however their structure and properties are sufficiently distinct that they are not classified as alkenes or olefins.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Hydrocarbons with two overlapping double bonds (C=C=C) are called allenes—the simplest such compound is itself called *allene*—and those with three or more overlapping bonds (C=C=C=C, C=C=C=C=C, etc.) are called cumulenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] A carbon–carbon double bond consists of a sigma bond and a pi bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This double bond is stronger than a single covalent bond: 611 kJ/mol vs.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Double bonds are shorter than single bonds with an average bond length of 1.33 Å (133 pm) vs 1.53 Å for a typical C-C single bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In one bonding model, the carbon atom of the double bond is sp2 hybridized.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The sp2 orbitals form sigma bonds to three atoms (the other carbon atom and two hydrogen atoms).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The unhybridized 2p atomic orbital, which lie perpendicular to the plane of the three sp2 orbitals, combine to form the pi bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This bond lies outside the main C–C axis, with half of the bond on one side of the molecule and a half on the other.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] With a strength of 65 kcal/mol, the pi bond is significantly weaker than the sigma bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Rotation about the carbon–carbon double bond is restricted because it incurs an energetic cost to break the alignment of the p orbitals on the two carbon atoms.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Consequently *cis* or *trans* isomers interconvert so slowly that they can be freely handled at ambient conditions without isomerization.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] More complex alkenes may be named with the *E*–*Z* notation for molecules with three or four different substituents (side groups).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For example, of the isomers of butene, the two methyl groups of (*Z*)-but-2-ene (a.k.a.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] *cis*-2-butene) appear on the same side of the double bond, and in (*E*)-but-2-ene (a.k.a.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] *trans*-2-butene) the methyl groups appear on opposite sides.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] These two isomers of butene have distinct properties.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] As predicted by the VSEPR model of electron pair repulsion, the molecular geometry of alkenes includes bond angles about each carbon atom in a double bond of about 120°.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The angle may vary because of steric strain introduced by nonbonded interactions between functional groups attached to the carbon atoms of the double bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For example, the C–C–C bond angle in propylene is 123.9°.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For bridged alkenes, Bredt's rule states that a double bond cannot occur at the bridgehead of a bridged ring system unless the rings are large enough.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Following Fawcett and defining *S* as the total number of non-bridgehead atoms in the rings, bicyclic systems require *S* ≥ 7 for stability and tricyclic systems require *S* ≥ 11.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In organic chemistry, the prefixes cis- and trans- are used to describe the positions of functional groups attached to carbon atoms joined by a double bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In Latin, *cis* and *trans* mean "on this side of" and "on the other side of" respectively.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Therefore, if the functional groups are both on the same side of the carbon chain, the bond is said to have **cis-** configuration, otherwise (i.e. the functional groups are on the opposite side of the carbon chain), the bond is said to have **trans-** configuration.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For there to be cis- and trans- configurations, there must be a carbon chain, or at least one functional group attached to each carbon that is the same for both.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] E- and Z- configuration can be used instead in a more general case where all four functional groups attached to carbon atoms in a double bond are different.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] E- and Z- are abbreviations of German words *zusammen* (together) and *entgegen* (opposite).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In E- and Z-isomerism, each functional group is assigned a priority based on the Cahn–Ingold–Prelog priority rules.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] If the two groups with higher priority are on the same side of the double bond, the bond is assigned **Z-** configuration, otherwise (i.e. the two groups with higher priority are on the opposite side of the double bond), the bond is assigned **E-** configuration.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Cis- and trans- configurations do not have a fixed relationship between **E**- and **Z**-configurations.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes having four or more carbon atoms can exist as structural isomers.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Most alkenes are also isomers of cycloalkanes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Many of these molecules exhibit *cis*–*trans* isomerism.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] There may also be chiral carbon atoms particularly within the larger molecules (from C5).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The number of potential isomers increases rapidly with additional carbon atoms.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Although the nomenclature is not followed widely, according to IUPAC, an alkene is an acyclic hydrocarbon with just one double bond between carbon atoms.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Olefins comprise a larger collection of cyclic and acyclic alkenes as well as dienes and polyenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] To form the root of the IUPAC names for straight-chain alkenes, change the *-an-* infix of the parent to *-en-*.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For example, **CH3-CH3** is the alkane *ethANe*.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The name of **CH2=CH2** is therefore *ethENe*.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For straight-chain alkenes with 4 or more carbon atoms, that name does not completely identify the compound.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Number the carbons in that chain starting from the end that is closest to the double bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Define the location *k* of the double bond as being the number of its first carbon.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Name the side groups (other than hydrogen) according to the appropriate rules.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Define the position of each side group as the number of the chain carbon it is attached to.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Write the position and name of each side group.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Write the names of the alkane with the same chain, replacing the "-ane" suffix by "*k*-ene".
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The position of the double bond is often inserted before the name of the chain (e.g.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] "2-pentene"), rather than before the suffix ("pent-2-ene").
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The positions need not be indicated if they are unique.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Note that the double bond may imply a different chain numbering than that used for the corresponding alkane: (H 3C) 3C–CH 2–CH 3 is "2,2-dimethyl pentane", whereas (H 3C) 3C–CH=CH 2 is "3,3-dimethyl 1-pentene".
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] More complex rules apply for polyenes and cycloalkenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] If the double bond of an acyclic mono-ene is not the first bond of the chain, the name as constructed above still does not completely identify the compound, because of *cis*–*trans* isomerism.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Then one must specify whether the two single C–C bonds adjacent to the double bond are on the same side of its plane, or on opposite sides.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For monoalkenes, the configuration is often indicated by the prefixes *cis*- (from Latin "on this side of") or *trans*- ("across", "on the other side of") before the name, respectively; as in *cis*-2-pentene or *trans*-2-butene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] More generally, *cis*–*trans* isomerism will exist if each of the two carbons of in the double bond has two different atoms or groups attached to it.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Accounting for these cases, the IUPAC recommends the more general E–Z notation, instead of the *cis* and *trans* prefixes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This notation considers the group with highest CIP priority in each of the two carbons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] If these two groups are on opposite sides of the double bond's plane, the configuration is labeled *E* (from the German *entgegen* meaning "opposite"); if they are on the same side, it is labeled *Z* (from German *zusammen*, "together").
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This labeling may be taught with mnemonic "*Z* means 'on ze zame zide'".
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] IUPAC recognizes two names for hydrocarbon groups containing carbon–carbon double bonds, the vinyl group and the allyl group.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Many of the physical properties of alkenes and alkanes are similar: they are colorless, nonpolar, and combustible.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The physical state depends on molecular mass: like the corresponding saturated hydrocarbons, the simplest alkenes (ethylene, propylene, and butene) are gases at room temperature.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Linear alkenes of approximately five to nineteen carbon atoms are liquids, and higher alkenes are waxy solids.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The melting point of the solids also increases with increase in molecular mass.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes generally have stronger smells than their corresponding alkanes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Strained alkenes, in particular, like norbornene and *trans*-cyclooctene are known to have strong, unpleasant odors, a fact consistent with the stronger π complexes they form with metal ions including copper.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Below is a list of the boiling and melting points of various alkenes with the corresponding alkane and alkyne analogues.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In the IR spectrum, the stretching/compression of C=C bond gives a peak at 1670–1600 cm−1.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The band is weak in symmetrical alkenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In 1H NMR spectroscopy, the hydrogen bonded to the carbon adjacent to double bonds has a δH of 4.5–6.5 ppm.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The double bond will also deshield the hydrogen attached to the carbons adjacent to sp2 carbons, and this generates δH=1.6–2 ppm peaks.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Cis/trans isomers are distinguishable due to different J-coupling effect.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Cis vicinal hydrogens will have coupling constants in the range of 6–14 Hz, whereas the trans will have coupling constants of 11–18 Hz.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In their 13C NMR spectra, double bonds also deshield the carbons, making them have low field shift.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] C=C double bonds usually have chemical shift of about 100–170 ppm.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Like most other hydrocarbons, alkenes combust to give carbon dioxide and water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The combustion of alkenes release less energy than burning same molarity of saturated ones with same number of carbons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This trend can be clearly seen in the list of standard enthalpy of combustion of hydrocarbons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes are relatively stable compounds, but are more reactive than alkanes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Most reactions of alkenes involve additions to this pi bond, forming new single bonds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes serve as a feedstock for the petrochemical industry because they can participate in a wide variety of reactions, prominently polymerization and alkylation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Except for ethylene, alkenes have two sites of reactivity: the carbon–carbon pi-bond and the presence of allylic CH centers.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The former dominates but the allylic sites are important too.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Hydrogenation involves the addition of H2 "across" the double bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Hydrogenation reactions usually require transition metal catalysts such as palladium on carbon or PtO2.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The total number of hydrogens that can be added to an unsaturated hydrocarbon depends on its degree of unsaturation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Comparable to hydrogenation is halogenation, the addition of a halogen molecule, such as Br2, resulting in a dihaloalkane.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Unlike hydrogenation, halogenation reactions do not require catalysts.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The reaction occurs in two steps, with a halonium ion as an intermediate.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Bromine test is used to test the saturation of hydrocarbons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The bromine test can also be used as an indication of the degree of unsaturation for unsaturated hydrocarbons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Bromine number is defined as gram of bromine able to react with 100g of product.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The π bonds of alkenes hydrocarbons are also susceptible to hydration.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The reaction usually requires strong acid as catalyst.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The first step in hydration often involves formation of a carbocation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The net result of the reaction will be an alcohol.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Hydrohalogenation involves addition of H−X to unsaturated hydrocarbons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This reaction results in new C−H and C−X σ bonds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The formation of the intermediate carbocation is selective and follows Markovnikov's rule.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The hydrohalogenation of alkene will result in haloalkane.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes add to dienes to give cyclohexenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This conversion is an example of a Diels-Alder reaction.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Such reaction proceed with retention of stereochemistry.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The rates are sensitive to electron-withdrawing or electron-donating substituents.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] When irradiated by UV-light, alkenes dimerize to give cyclobutanes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes react with ozone, leading to the scission of the double bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] When treated with a hot concentrated, acidified solution of KMnO4, alkenes are cleaved to form ketones and/or carboxylic acids.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The stoichiometry of the reaction is sensitive to conditions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This reaction and the ozonolysis can be used to determine the position of a double bond in an unknown alkene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This reaction is called dihydroxylation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In the presence of an appropriate photosensitiser, such as methylene blue and light, alkenes can undergo reaction with reactive oxygen species generated by the photosensitiser, such as hydroxyl radicals, singlet oxygen or superoxide ion.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Reactions of the excited sensitizer can involve electron or hydrogen transfer, usually with a reducing substrate (Type I reaction) or interaction with oxygen (Type II reaction).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] These various alternative processes and reactions can be controlled by choice of specific reaction conditions, leading to a wide range of products.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Terminal alkenes are precursors to polymers via processes termed polymerization.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Some polymerizations are of great economic significance, as they generate the plastics polyethylene and polypropylene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Polymers from alkene are usually referred to as *polyolefins* although they contain no olefins.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Polymerization can proceed via diverse mechanisms.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Conjugated dienes such as buta-1,3-diene and isoprene (2-methylbuta-1,3-diene) also produce polymers, one example being natural rubber.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The presence of a C=C π bond in unsaturated hydrocarbons weakens the dissociation energy of the allylic C−H bonds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Thus, these groupings are susceptible to free radical substitution at these C-H sites as well as addition reactions at the C=C site.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In the presence of radical initiators, allylic C-H bonds can be halogenated.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The presence of two C=C bonds flanking one methylene, i.e., doubly allylic, results in particularly weak HC-H bonds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The high reactivity of these situations is the basis for certain free radical reactions, manifested in the chemistry of drying oils.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes undergo olefin metathesis, which cleaves and interchanges the substituents of the alkene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In transition metal alkene complexes, alkenes serve as ligands for metals.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In this case, the π electron density is donated to the metal d orbitals.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The stronger the donation is, the stronger the back bonding from the metal d orbital to π* anti-bonding orbital of the alkene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This effect lowers the bond order of the alkene and increases the C-C bond length.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] One example is the complex PtCl3(C2H4)]−.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] These complexes are related to the mechanisms of metal-catalyzed reactions of unsaturated hydrocarbons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes are produced by hydrocarbon cracking.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Raw materials are mostly natural-gas condensate components (principally ethane and propane) in the US and Mideast and naphtha in Europe and Asia.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkanes are broken apart at high temperatures, often in the presence of a zeolite catalyst, to produce a mixture of primarily aliphatic alkenes and lower molecular weight alkanes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The mixture is feedstock and temperature dependent, and separated by fractional distillation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This is mainly used for the manufacture of small alkenes (up to six carbons).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Related to this is catalytic dehydrogenation, where an alkane loses hydrogen at high temperatures to produce a corresponding alkene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This is the reverse of the catalytic hydrogenation of alkenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This process is also known as reforming.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Both processes are endothermic and are driven towards the alkene at high temperatures by entropy.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Catalytic synthesis of higher α-alkenes (of the type RCH=CH2) can also be achieved by a reaction of ethylene with the organometallic compound triethylaluminium in the presence of nickel, cobalt, or platinum.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] One of the principal methods for alkene synthesis in the laboratory is the elimination reaction of alkyl halides, alcohols, and similar compounds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Most common is the β-elimination via the E2 or E1 mechanism.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] A commercially significant example is the production of vinyl chloride.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The E2 mechanism provides a more reliable β-elimination method than E1 for most alkene syntheses.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Most E2 eliminations start with an alkyl halide or alkyl sulfonate ester (such as a tosylate or triflate).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] When an alkyl halide is used, the reaction is called a dehydrohalogenation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For unsymmetrical products, the more substituted alkenes (those with fewer hydrogens attached to the C=C) tend to predominate (see Zaitsev's rule).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Two common methods of elimination reactions are dehydrohalogenation of alkyl halides and dehydration of alcohols.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] A typical example is shown below; note that if possible, the H is *anti* to the leaving group, even though this leads to the less stable *Z*-isomer.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes can be synthesized from alcohols via dehydration, in which case water is lost via the E1 mechanism.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] An alcohol may also be converted to a better leaving group (e.g., xanthate), so as to allow a milder *syn*-elimination such as the Chugaev elimination and the Grieco elimination.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Related reactions include eliminations by β-haloethers (the Boord olefin synthesis; also a selenium-based elimination discussed below) and esters (ester pyrolysis).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] A thioketone and a phosphite ester combined (the Corey-Winter olefination) or diphosphorus tetraiodide will deoxygenate glycols to alkenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes can be prepared indirectly from alkyl amines.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The amine or ammonia is not a suitable leaving group, so the amine is first either alkylated (as in the Hofmann elimination) or oxidized to an amine oxide (the Cope reaction) to render a smooth elimination possible.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The Hofmann elimination is unusual in that the *less* substituted (non-Zaitsev) alkene is usually the major product.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes are generated from α-halosulfones in the Ramberg–Bäcklund reaction, via a three-membered ring sulfone intermediate.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Another important class of methods for alkene synthesis involves construction of a new carbon–carbon double bond by coupling or condensation of a carbonyl compound (such as an aldehyde or ketone) to a carbanion or its equivalent.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Knoevenagel condensations are a related class of reactions that convert carbonyls into alkenes.Well-known methods are called *olefinations*.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The Wittig reaction is illustrative, but other related methods are known, including the Horner–Wadsworth–Emmons reaction.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The Wittig reaction involves reaction of an aldehyde or ketone with a Wittig reagent (or phosphorane) of the type Ph3P=CHR to produce an alkene and Ph3P=O.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The Wittig reagent is itself prepared easily from triphenylphosphine and an alkyl halide.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Related to the Wittig reaction is the Peterson olefination, which uses silicon-based reagents in place of the phosphorane.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] This reaction allows for the selection of *E*- or *Z*-products.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] If an *E*-product is desired, another alternative is the Julia olefination, which uses the carbanion generated from a phenyl sulfone.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The Takai olefination based on an organochromium intermediate also delivers E-products.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] A titanium compound, Tebbe's reagent, is useful for the synthesis of methylene compounds; in this case, even esters and amides react.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] A pair of ketones or aldehydes can be deoxygenated to generate an alkene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Symmetrical alkenes can be prepared from a single aldehyde or ketone coupling with itself, using titanium metal reduction (the McMurry reaction).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] If different ketones are to be coupled, a more complicated method is required, such as the Barton–Kellogg reaction.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] A single ketone can also be converted to the corresponding alkene via its tosylhydrazone, using sodium methoxide (the Bamford–Stevens reaction) or an alkyllithium (the Shapiro reaction).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The formation of longer alkenes via the step-wise polymerisation of smaller ones is appealing, as ethylene (the smallest alkene) is both inexpensive and readily available, with hundreds of millions of tonnes produced annually.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The Ziegler–Natta process allows for the formation of very long chains, for instance those used for polyethylene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Where shorter chains are wanted, as they for the production of surfactants, then processes incorporating a olefin metathesis step, such as the Shell higher olefin process are important.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Olefin metathesis is also used commercially for the interconversion of ethylene and 2-butene to propylene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Transition metal catalyzed hydrovinylation is another important alkene synthesis process starting from alkene itself.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] It involves the addition of a hydrogen and a vinyl group (or an alkenyl group) across a double bond.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Reduction of alkynes is a useful method for the stereoselective synthesis of disubstituted alkenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Reduction of the alkyne by sodium metal in liquid ammonia gives the *trans*-alkene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] For the preparation multisubstituted alkenes, carbometalation of alkynes can give rise to a large variety of alkene derivatives.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Alkenes can be synthesized from other alkenes via rearrangement reactions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Besides olefin metathesis (described above), many pericyclic reactions can be used such as the ene reaction and the Cope rearrangement.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] In the Diels–Alder reaction, a cyclohexene derivative is prepared from a diene and a reactive or electron-deficient alkene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Unsaturated hydrocarbons are widely used to produce plastics, medicines, and other useful materials.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Plants are the main natural source of alkenes in the form of terpenes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] Many of the most vivid natural pigments are terpenes; e.g. lycopene (red in tomatoes), carotene (orange in carrots), and xanthophylls (yellow in egg yolk).
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The simplest of all alkenes, ethylene is a signaling molecule that influences the ripening of plants.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] The Curiosity rover discovered on Mars long chain alkanes with up to 12 consecutive carbon atoms.
[src:1-phenylethanol/alkene] They could be derived from either abiotic or biological sources.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] An **aqueous solution** is a solution in which the solvent is water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] It is mostly shown in chemical equations by appending (aq) to the relevant chemical formula.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] For example, a solution of table salt, also known as sodium chloride (NaCl), in water would be represented as Na+(aq) + Cl−(aq).
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] The word *aqueous* (which comes from *aqua*) means pertaining to, related to, similar to, or dissolved in, water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] As water is an excellent solvent and is also naturally abundant, it is a ubiquitous solvent in chemistry.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Since water is frequently used as the solvent in experiments, the word solution refers to an aqueous solution, unless the solvent is specified.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] A *non-aqueous solution* is a solution in which the solvent is a liquid, but is not water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Substances that are *hydrophobic* ('water-fearing') do not dissolve well in water, whereas those that are *hydrophilic* ('water-loving') do.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] An example of a hydrophilic substance is sodium chloride.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] In an aqueous solution the hydrogen ions (H+) and hydroxide ions (OH−) are in Arrhenius balance ([H+] [OH−] = *Kw* = 1 × 10−14 at 298 K).
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Acids and bases are aqueous solutions, as part of their Arrhenius definitions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] An example of an Arrhenius acid is hydrogen chloride (HCl) because of its dissociation of the hydrogen ion when dissolved in water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is an Arrhenius base because it dissociates the hydroxide ion when it is dissolved in water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions may contain, especially in the alkaline zone or subjected to radiolysis, hydrated atomic hydrogen and hydrated electrons.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions that conduct electric current efficiently contain "strong" electrolytes, while those that conduct poorly are attributable to weaker electrolytes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] The former substances are completely, or at least substantially, ionized in water; conversely, the weak electrolytes exhibit relatively limited ionization in water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] The ability of ions to move freely through a solvent is a characteristic of an aqueous strong electrolyte solution; the solutes in a weaker electrolyte solution are present as ions, but only to a small degree.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Non-electrolytes, conversely, are substances that dissolve in water, yet maintain their molecular integrity: they do not dissociate into ions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Examples include sugars, urea, glycerol, and ethanol.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Reactions in aqueous solutions are usually metathesis reactions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Metathesis reactions are another term for double-displacement; that is, when a cation displaces to form an ionic bond with the other anion.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] The cation bonded with the latter anion will dissociate and bond with the other anion.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] A common metathesis reaction in aqueous solutions is a precipitation reaction.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] This reaction occurs when two aqueous strong electrolyte solutions mix and produce an insoluble solid, also known as a precipitate.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] The ability of a substance to dissolve in water is determined by whether the substance can match or exceed the strong attractive forces that water molecules generate between themselves.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] If the substance lacks the ability to dissolve in water, the molecules form a precipitate.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] When writing the equations of precipitation reactions, it is essential to determine the precipitate.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] To determine the precipitate, one must consult a chart of solubility.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Soluble compounds are aqueous, while insoluble compounds are the precipitate.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] Complete ionic equations and net ionic equations are used to show dissociated ions in metathesis reactions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/aqueous-solution] When performing calculations regarding the reacting of one or more aqueous solutions, in general one must know the concentration, or molarity, of the aqueous solutions.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] It is a colorless liquid with a characteristic odor similar to that of bitter almonds and cherry, and is commonly used in cherry-flavored sodas.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] A component of bitter almond oil, benzaldehyde can be extracted from a number of other natural sources.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Synthetic benzaldehyde is the flavoring agent in imitation almond extract, which is used to flavor cakes and other baked goods.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde was first extracted in 1803 by the French pharmacist Martrès.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] His experiments focused on elucidating the nature of amygdalin, the poisonous compound found in bitter almonds, the fruit of *Prunus dulcis*.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Further work on the oil by Pierre Robiquet and Antoine Boutron Charlard, two French chemists, produced benzaldehyde.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] In 1832, Friedrich Wöhler and Justus von Liebig first synthesized benzaldehyde.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde can be produced from both petroleum-based chemicals or plant-derived chemicals.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Synthetic benzaldehyde is primarily produced using liquid phase chlorination and oxidation of toluene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Numerous other methods have been developed, such as the partial oxidation of benzyl alcohol, alkali hydrolysis of benzal chloride, and the carbonylation of benzene (the Gatterman-Koch reaction).
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde and similar chemicals occur naturally in many foods.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Most of the benzaldehyde that people eat is from natural plant foods, such as almonds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Almonds, apricot seeds, apple seeds, and cherry seed contain significant amounts of amygdalin.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] This glycoside breaks up under enzyme catalysis into benzaldehyde, hydrogen cyanide and two equivalents of glucose.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde contributes to the scent of oyster mushrooms (*Pleurotus ostreatus*).
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde is easily oxidized to benzoic acid in air at room temperature, causing a common impurity in laboratory samples.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Since the boiling point of benzoic acid is much higher than that of benzaldehyde, it may be purified by distillation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzyl alcohol can be formed from benzaldehyde by means of hydrogenation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Reaction of benzaldehyde with anhydrous sodium acetate and acetic anhydride yields cinnamic acid, while alcoholic potassium cyanide can be used to catalyze the condensation of benzaldehyde to benzoin.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde undergoes disproportionation upon treatment with concentrated alkali (Cannizzaro reaction): one molecule of the aldehyde is reduced to the benzyl alcohol and another molecule is simultaneously oxidized to benzoic acid.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] With diols, including many sugars, benzaldehyde condenses to form benzylidene acetals.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde is commonly employed to confer almond flavor to foods and scented products, including e-cigarette liquids.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] It is sometimes used in cosmetics products.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] In industrial settings, benzaldehyde is used chiefly as a precursor to other organic compounds, ranging from pharmaceuticals to plastic additives.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] The aniline dye malachite green is prepared from benzaldehyde and dimethylaniline.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde is also a precursor to certain acridine dyes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Via aldol condensations, benzaldehyde is converted into derivatives of cinnamaldehyde and styrene.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] The resulting cyanohydrin is hydrolysed to mandelic acid.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] (The scheme above depicts only one of the two formed enantiomers).
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde is used as a bee repellent.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] A small amount of benzaldehyde solution is placed on a fume board near the honeycombs.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] The bees then move away from the honey combs to avoid the fumes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] The beekeeper can then remove the honey frames from the bee hive with less risk to both bees and beekeeper.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde reacts with nitroethane in the presence of a catalyst to produce phenyl-2-nitropropene, a precursor to amphetamine and other chemicals.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] As used in food, cosmetics, pharmaceuticals, and soap, benzaldehyde is "generally regarded as safe" (GRAS) by the US FDA and FEMA.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] This status was reaffirmed after a review in 2005.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] It is accepted in the European Union as a flavoring agent.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Toxicology studies indicate that it is safe and non-carcinogenic in the concentrations used for foods and cosmetics, and may even have anti-carcinogenic (anti-cancer) properties.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] For a 70 kg human, the lethal dose is estimated at 50 ml.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] An acceptable daily intake of 15 mg/day has been identified for benzaldehyde by the United States Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] Benzaldehyde does not accumulate in human tissues.
[src:1-phenylethanol/benzaldehyde] It is metabolized and then excreted in urine.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The **boiling point** of a substance is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of a liquid equals the pressure surrounding the liquid and the liquid changes into a vapor.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point of a liquid varies depending upon the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] A liquid in a partial vacuum, i.e., under a lower pressure, has a lower boiling point than when that liquid is at atmospheric pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Because of this, water boils at 100 °C, rounded from scientific precision of 99.97 °C (211.95 °F), under standard pressure at sea level, but at 93.4 °C (200.1 °F) at 1,905 metres (6,250 ft) altitude.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] For a given pressure, different liquids will boil at different temperatures.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The **normal boiling point** (also called the **atmospheric boiling point** or the **atmospheric pressure boiling point**) of a liquid is the special case in which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the defined atmospheric pressure at sea level, one atmosphere.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] At that temperature, the vapor pressure of the liquid becomes sufficient to overcome atmospheric pressure and allow bubbles of vapor to form inside the bulk of the liquid.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The **standard boiling point** has been defined by IUPAC since 1982 as the temperature at which boiling occurs under a pressure of one bar.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The heat of vaporization is the energy required to transform a given quantity (a mol, kg, pound, etc.) of a substance from a liquid into a gas at a given pressure (often atmospheric pressure).
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Liquids may change to a vapor at temperatures below their boiling points through the process of evaporation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Evaporation is a surface phenomenon in which molecules located near the liquid's edge, not contained by enough liquid pressure on that side, escape into the surroundings as vapor.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] On the other hand, boiling is a process in which molecules anywhere in the liquid escape, resulting in the formation of vapor bubbles within the liquid.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] A *saturated liquid* contains as much thermal energy as it can without boiling (or conversely a *saturated vapor* contains as little thermal energy as it can without condensing).
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] If the pressure in a system remains constant (isobaric), a vapor at saturation temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as thermal energy (heat) is removed.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation temperature and pressure will boil into its vapor phase as additional thermal energy is applied.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point corresponds to the temperature at which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Thus, the boiling point is dependent on the pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Boiling points may be published with respect to the NIST, USA standard pressure of 101.325 kPa (1 atm), or the IUPAC standard pressure of 100.000 kPa (1 bar).
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] At higher elevations, where the atmospheric pressure is much lower, the boiling point is also lower.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point increases with increased pressure up to the critical point, where the gas and liquid properties become identical.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be increased beyond the critical point.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Likewise, the boiling point decreases with decreasing pressure until the triple point is reached.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be reduced below the triple point.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] If the temperature in a system remains constant (an *isothermal* system), vapor at saturation pressure and temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as the system pressure is increased.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation pressure and temperature will tend to flash into its vapor phase as system pressure is decreased.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] There are two conventions regarding the *standard boiling point of water*: The *normal boiling point* is commonly given as 100 °C (212 °F) (actually 99.97 °C (211.9 °F) following the thermodynamic definition of the Celsius scale based on the kelvin) at a pressure of 1 atm (101.325 kPa).
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The IUPAC-recommended *standard boiling point of water* at a standard pressure of 100 kPa (1 bar) is 99.61 °C (211.3 °F).
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] For comparison, on top of Mount Everest, at 8,848 m (29,029 ft) elevation, the pressure is about 34 kPa (255 Torr) and the boiling point of water is 71 °C (160 °F).
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The Celsius temperature scale was defined until 1954 by two points: 0 °C being defined by the water freezing point and 100 °C being defined by the water boiling point at standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The higher the vapor pressure of a liquid at a given temperature, the lower the normal boiling point (i.e., the boiling point at atmospheric pressure) of the liquid.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The vapor pressure chart to the right has graphs of the vapor pressures versus temperatures for a variety of liquids.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] As can be seen in the chart, the liquids with the highest vapor pressures have the lowest normal boiling points.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] For example, at any given temperature, methyl chloride has the highest vapor pressure of any of the liquids in the chart.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] It also has the lowest normal boiling point (−24.2 °C), which is where the vapor pressure curve of methyl chloride (the blue line) intersects the horizontal pressure line of one atmosphere (atm) of absolute vapor pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The critical point of a liquid is the highest temperature (and pressure) it will actually boil at.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The element with the lowest boiling point is helium.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Both the boiling points of rhenium and tungsten exceed 5000 K at standard pressure; because it is difficult to measure extreme temperatures precisely without bias, both have been cited in the literature as having the higher boiling point.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] As can be seen from the above plot of the logarithm of the vapor pressure vs. the temperature for any given pure chemical compound, its normal boiling point can serve as an indication of that compound's overall volatility.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] A given pure compound has only one normal boiling point, if any, and a compound's normal boiling point and melting point can serve as characteristic physical properties for that compound, listed in reference books.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The higher a compound's normal boiling point, the less volatile that compound is overall, and conversely, the lower a compound's normal boiling point, the more volatile that compound is overall.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Some compounds decompose at higher temperatures before reaching their normal boiling point, or sometimes even their melting point.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] For a stable compound, the boiling point ranges from its triple point to its critical point, depending on the external pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Beyond its triple point, a compound's normal boiling point, if any, is higher than its melting point.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Beyond the critical point, a compound's liquid and vapor phases merge into one phase, which may be called a superheated gas.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] At any given temperature, if a compound's normal boiling point is lower, then that compound will generally exist as a gas at atmospheric external pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] If the compound's normal boiling point is higher, then that compound can exist as a liquid or solid at that given temperature at atmospheric external pressure, and will so exist in equilibrium with its vapor (if volatile) if its vapors are contained.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] If a compound's vapors are not contained, then some volatile compounds can eventually evaporate away in spite of their higher boiling points.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] In general, compounds with ionic bonds have high normal boiling points, if they do not decompose before reaching such high temperatures.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Many metals have high boiling points, but not all.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Very generally—with other factors being equal—in compounds with covalently bonded molecules, as the size of the molecule (or molecular mass) increases, the normal boiling point increases.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] When the molecular size becomes that of a macromolecule, polymer, or otherwise very large, the compound often decomposes at high temperature before the boiling point is reached.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Another factor that affects the normal boiling point of a compound is the polarity of its molecules.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] As the polarity of a compound's molecules increases, its normal boiling point increases, other factors being equal.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Closely related is the ability of a molecule to form hydrogen bonds (in the liquid state), which makes it harder for molecules to leave the liquid state and thus increases the normal boiling point of the compound.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Simple carboxylic acids dimerize by forming hydrogen bonds between molecules.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] A minor factor affecting boiling points is the shape of a molecule.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Making the shape of a molecule more compact tends to lower the normal boiling point slightly compared to an equivalent molecule with more surface area.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Most volatile compounds (anywhere near ambient temperatures) go through an intermediate liquid phase while warming up from a solid phase to eventually transform to a vapor phase.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] By comparison to boiling, a sublimation is a physical transformation in which a solid turns directly into vapor, which happens in a few select cases such as with carbon dioxide at atmospheric pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] For such compounds, a sublimation point is a temperature at which a solid turning directly into vapor has a vapor pressure equal to the external pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] In the preceding section, boiling points of pure compounds were covered.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Vapor pressures and boiling points of substances can be affected by the presence of dissolved impurities (solutes) or other miscible compounds, the degree of effect depending on the concentration of the impurities or other compounds.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The presence of non-volatile impurities such as salts or compounds of a volatility far lower than the main component compound decreases its mole fraction and the solution's volatility, and thus raises the normal boiling point in proportion to the concentration of the solutes.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] This effect is called **boiling point elevation**.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] As a common example, salt water boils at a higher temperature than pure water.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] In other mixtures of miscible compounds (components), there may be two or more components of varying volatility, each having its own pure component boiling point at any given pressure.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The presence of other volatile components in a mixture affects the vapor pressures and thus boiling points and dew points of all the components in the mixture.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] The dew point is a temperature at which a vapor condenses into a liquid.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Furthermore, at any given temperature, the composition of the vapor is different from the composition of the liquid in most such cases.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] In order to illustrate these effects between the volatile components in a mixture, a **boiling point diagram** is commonly used.
[src:1-phenylethanol/boiling-point] Distillation is a process of boiling and [usually] condensation which takes advantage of these differences in composition between liquid and vapor phases.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] This registry includes all substances described since 1957, plus some substances from as far back as the early 1800s.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] It is a chemical database that includes organic and inorganic compounds, minerals, isotopes, alloys, mixtures, and nonstructurable materials (UVCBs - substances of **u**nknown or **v**ariable composition, **c**omplex reaction products, or **b**iological origin).
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS RNs are generally serial numbers (with a check digit), so they do not contain any information about the structures themselves the way SMILES and InChI strings do.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry is an authoritative collection of disclosed chemical substance information.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] It identifies more than 204 million unique organic and inorganic substances and 69 million protein and DNA sequences, plus additional information about each substance.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] It is updated with around 15,000 additional new substances daily.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] The full registry is available on a paid subscription basis.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] A collection of almost 500 thousand CAS registry numbers is made available under a CC BY-NC license at ACS Commons Chemistry.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] Historically, chemicals have been identified by a wide variety of synonyms and properties.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] One of the biggest challenges in the early development of substance indexing, a task undertaken by the Chemical Abstracts Service, was in identifying if a substance in literature was new or if it had been previously discovered.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] Well-known chemicals may be known via multiple generic, historical, commercial, and/or (black)-market names, and even systematic nomenclature based on structure alone was not universally useful.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] An algorithm was developed to translate the structural formula of a chemical into a computer-searchable table, which provided a basis for the service that listed each chemical with its CAS Registry Number, the CAS Chemical Registry System, which became operational in 1965.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] CAS Registry Numbers (CAS RN) are simple and regular, convenient for database searches.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] They offer a reliable, common and international link to every specific substance across the various nomenclatures and disciplines used by branches of science, industry, and regulatory bodies.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] Almost all molecule databases today allow searching by CAS Registry Number, and it is used as a global standard.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS Registry Number has no inherent meaning, but is assigned in sequential, increasing order when the substance is identified by CAS scientists for inclusion in the CAS Registry database.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] A CAS RN is separated by hyphens into three parts, the first consisting from two up to seven digits, the second consisting of two digits, and the third consisting of a single digit serving as a check digit.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] This format gives CAS a maximum capacity of 1,000,000,000 unique numbers.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] The check digit is found by taking the last digit times 1, the preceding digit times 2, the preceding digit times 3 etc., adding all these up and computing the sum modulo 10.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry accepts entries that are (1) descriptive of matter consisting of chemical elements, (2) distinct from existing ones, and (3) present in scientific literature.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] The definition of "distinct" excludes different phases of the same substance (e.g. water and ice), but includes narrowing of existing concepts (e.g. carbon vs. graphite and diamond; isotope-labelled forms of an existing compound).
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] The Chemical Abstracts Service subscription includes an official search service.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] The Service ("CAS Data") provides information on the chemical itself, its mentions in published scholarly works and patents, curated biological and chemical reaction data, as well as listings of commercial sources and details on using a substance in a formulation.
[src:1-phenylethanol/cas-registry-number] A subset of the registry can be accessed through the free-of-charge CAS Common Chemistry, which provides identifying information for the chemical in question.
